#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:4
msgid "Quickstart"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:8
msgid ""
"Eager to get started? This page gives a good introduction in how to get "
"started with Requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:11
msgid "First, make sure that:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:13
msgid "Requests is :ref:`installed <install>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:14
msgid "Requests is :ref:`up-to-date <updates>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:17
msgid "Let's get started with some simple examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:21
msgid "Make a Request"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:23
msgid "Making a request with Requests is very simple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:25
msgid "Begin by importing the Requests module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:27
msgid ">>> import requests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:29
msgid ""
"Now, let's try to get a webpage. For this example, let's get GitHub's public "
"timeline::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:32
msgid ">>> r = requests.get('https://api.github.com/events')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:34
msgid ""
"Now, we have a :class:`Response <requests.Response>` object called ``r``. We "
"can get all the information we need from this object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:37
msgid ""
"Requests' simple API means that all forms of HTTP request are as obvious. "
"For example, this is how you make an HTTP POST request::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:40
msgid ""
">>> r = requests.post('https://httpbin.org/post', data={'key': 'value'})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:42
msgid ""
"Nice, right? What about the other HTTP request types: PUT, DELETE, HEAD and "
"OPTIONS? These are all just as simple::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:45
msgid ""
">>> r = requests.put('https://httpbin.org/put', data={'key': 'value'})\n"
">>> r = requests.delete('https://httpbin.org/delete')\n"
">>> r = requests.head('https://httpbin.org/get')\n"
">>> r = requests.options('https://httpbin.org/get')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:50
msgid ""
"That's all well and good, but it's also only the start of what Requests can "
"do."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:55
msgid "Passing Parameters In URLs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:57
msgid ""
"You often want to send some sort of data in the URL's query string. If you "
"were constructing the URL by hand, this data would be given as key/value "
"pairs in the URL after a question mark, e.g. ``httpbin.org/get?key=val``. "
"Requests allows you to provide these arguments as a dictionary of strings, "
"using the ``params`` keyword argument. As an example, if you wanted to pass "
"``key1=value1`` and ``key2=value2`` to ``httpbin.org/get``, you would use "
"the following code::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:65
msgid ""
">>> payload = {'key1': 'value1', 'key2': 'value2'}\n"
">>> r = requests.get('https://httpbin.org/get', params=payload)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:68
msgid ""
"You can see that the URL has been correctly encoded by printing the URL::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:70
msgid ""
">>> print(r.url)\n"
"https://httpbin.org/get?key2=value2&key1=value1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:73
msgid ""
"Note that any dictionary key whose value is ``None`` will not be added to "
"the URL's query string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:76
msgid "You can also pass a list of items as a value::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:78
msgid ""
">>> payload = {'key1': 'value1', 'key2': ['value2', 'value3']}\n"
"\n"
">>> r = requests.get('https://httpbin.org/get', params=payload)\n"
">>> print(r.url)\n"
"https://httpbin.org/get?key1=value1&key2=value2&key2=value3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:85
msgid "Response Content"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:87
msgid ""
"We can read the content of the server's response. Consider the GitHub "
"timeline again::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:90
msgid ""
">>> import requests\n"
"\n"
">>> r = requests.get('https://api.github.com/events')\n"
">>> r.text\n"
"'[{\"repository\":{\"open_issues\":0,\"url\":\"https://github.com/..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:96
msgid ""
"Requests will automatically decode content from the server. Most unicode "
"charsets are seamlessly decoded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:99
msgid ""
"When you make a request, Requests makes educated guesses about the encoding "
"of the response based on the HTTP headers. The text encoding guessed by "
"Requests is used when you access ``r.text``. You can find out what encoding "
"Requests is using, and change it, using the ``r.encoding`` property::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:104
msgid ""
">>> r.encoding\n"
"'utf-8'\n"
">>> r.encoding = 'ISO-8859-1'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:108
msgid ""
"If you change the encoding, Requests will use the new value of ``r."
"encoding`` whenever you call ``r.text``. You might want to do this in any "
"situation where you can apply special logic to work out what the encoding of "
"the content will be. For example, HTML and XML have the ability to specify "
"their encoding in their body. In situations like this, you should use ``r."
"content`` to find the encoding, and then set ``r.encoding``. This will let "
"you use ``r.text`` with the correct encoding."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:116
msgid ""
"Requests will also use custom encodings in the event that you need them. If "
"you have created your own encoding and registered it with the ``codecs`` "
"module, you can simply use the codec name as the value of ``r.encoding`` and "
"Requests will handle the decoding for you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:122
msgid "Binary Response Content"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:124
msgid "You can also access the response body as bytes, for non-text requests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:126
msgid ""
">>> r.content\n"
"b'[{\"repository\":{\"open_issues\":0,\"url\":\"https://github.com/..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:129
msgid ""
"The ``gzip`` and ``deflate`` transfer-encodings are automatically decoded "
"for you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:131
msgid ""
"The ``br``  transfer-encoding is automatically decoded for you if a Brotli "
"library like `brotli <https://pypi.org/project/brotli>`_ or `brotlicffi "
"<https://pypi.org/project/brotlicffi>`_ is installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:134
msgid ""
"For example, to create an image from binary data returned by a request, you "
"can use the following code::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:137
msgid ""
">>> from PIL import Image\n"
">>> from io import BytesIO\n"
"\n"
">>> i = Image.open(BytesIO(r.content))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:144
msgid "JSON Response Content"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:146
msgid ""
"There's also a builtin JSON decoder, in case you're dealing with JSON data::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:148
msgid ""
">>> import requests\n"
"\n"
">>> r = requests.get('https://api.github.com/events')\n"
">>> r.json()\n"
"[{'repository': {'open_issues': 0, 'url': 'https://github.com/..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:154
msgid ""
"In case the JSON decoding fails, ``r.json()`` raises an exception. For "
"example, if the response gets a 204 (No Content), or if the response "
"contains invalid JSON, attempting ``r.json()`` raises ``requests.exceptions."
"JSONDecodeError``. This wrapper exception provides interoperability for "
"multiple exceptions that may be thrown by different python versions and json "
"serialization libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:160
msgid ""
"It should be noted that the success of the call to ``r.json()`` does **not** "
"indicate the success of the response. Some servers may return a JSON object "
"in a failed response (e.g. error details with HTTP 500). Such JSON will be "
"decoded and returned. To check that a request is successful, use ``r."
"raise_for_status()`` or check ``r.status_code`` is what you expect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:168
msgid "Raw Response Content"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:170
msgid ""
"In the rare case that you'd like to get the raw socket response from the "
"server, you can access ``r.raw``. If you want to do this, make sure you set "
"``stream=True`` in your initial request. Once you do, you can do this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:174
msgid ""
">>> r = requests.get('https://api.github.com/events', stream=True)\n"
"\n"
">>> r.raw\n"
"<urllib3.response.HTTPResponse object at 0x101194810>\n"
"\n"
">>> r.raw.read(10)\n"
"b'\\x1f\\x8b\\x08\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x03'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:182
msgid ""
"In general, however, you should use a pattern like this to save what is "
"being streamed to a file::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:185
msgid ""
"with open(filename, 'wb') as fd:\n"
"    for chunk in r.iter_content(chunk_size=128):\n"
"        fd.write(chunk)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:189
msgid ""
"Using ``Response.iter_content`` will handle a lot of what you would "
"otherwise have to handle when using ``Response.raw`` directly. When "
"streaming a download, the above is the preferred and recommended way to "
"retrieve the content. Note that ``chunk_size`` can be freely adjusted to a "
"number that may better fit your use cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:197
msgid ""
"An important note about using ``Response.iter_content`` versus ``Response."
"raw``. ``Response.iter_content`` will automatically decode the ``gzip`` and "
"``deflate`` transfer-encodings.  ``Response.raw`` is a raw stream of bytes "
"-- it does not transform the response content.  If you really need access to "
"the bytes as they were returned, use ``Response.raw``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:207
msgid "Custom Headers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:209
msgid ""
"If you'd like to add HTTP headers to a request, simply pass in a ``dict`` to "
"the ``headers`` parameter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:212
msgid "For example, we didn't specify our user-agent in the previous example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:214
msgid ""
">>> url = 'https://api.github.com/some/endpoint'\n"
">>> headers = {'user-agent': 'my-app/0.0.1'}\n"
"\n"
">>> r = requests.get(url, headers=headers)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:219
msgid ""
"Note: Custom headers are given less precedence than more specific sources of "
"information. For instance:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:221
msgid ""
"Authorization headers set with `headers=` will be overridden if credentials "
"are specified in ``.netrc``, which in turn will be overridden by the  "
"``auth=`` parameter. Requests will search for the netrc file at `~/.netrc`, "
"`~/_netrc`, or at the path specified by the `NETRC` environment variable. "
"Check details in :ref:`netrc authentication <authentication>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:226
msgid "Authorization headers will be removed if you get redirected off-host."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:227
msgid ""
"Proxy-Authorization headers will be overridden by proxy credentials provided "
"in the URL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:228
msgid ""
"Content-Length headers will be overridden when we can determine the length "
"of the content."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:230
msgid ""
"Furthermore, Requests does not change its behavior at all based on which "
"custom headers are specified. The headers are simply passed on into the "
"final request."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:232
msgid ""
"Note: All header values must be a ``string``, bytestring, or unicode. While "
"permitted, it's advised to avoid passing unicode header values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:235
msgid "More complicated POST requests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:237
msgid ""
"Typically, you want to send some form-encoded data — much like an HTML form. "
"To do this, simply pass a dictionary to the ``data`` argument. Your "
"dictionary of data will automatically be form-encoded when the request is "
"made::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:241
msgid ""
">>> payload = {'key1': 'value1', 'key2': 'value2'}\n"
"\n"
">>> r = requests.post('https://httpbin.org/post', data=payload)\n"
">>> print(r.text)\n"
"{\n"
"  ...\n"
"  \"form\": {\n"
"    \"key2\": \"value2\",\n"
"    \"key1\": \"value1\"\n"
"  },\n"
"  ...\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:254
msgid ""
"The ``data`` argument can also have multiple values for each key. This can "
"be done by making ``data`` either a list of tuples or a dictionary with "
"lists as values. This is particularly useful when the form has multiple "
"elements that use the same key::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:259
msgid ""
">>> payload_tuples = [('key1', 'value1'), ('key1', 'value2')]\n"
">>> r1 = requests.post('https://httpbin.org/post', data=payload_tuples)\n"
">>> payload_dict = {'key1': ['value1', 'value2']}\n"
">>> r2 = requests.post('https://httpbin.org/post', data=payload_dict)\n"
">>> print(r1.text)\n"
"{\n"
"  ...\n"
"  \"form\": {\n"
"    \"key1\": [\n"
"      \"value1\",\n"
"      \"value2\"\n"
"    ]\n"
"  },\n"
"  ...\n"
"}\n"
">>> # httpbin may embed non-deterministic metadata,\n"
">>> # so we only compare our submitted data here.\n"
">>> r1.json()['form'] == r2.json()['form']\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:279
msgid ""
"There are times that you may want to send data that is not form-encoded. If "
"you pass in a ``string`` instead of a ``dict``, that data will be posted "
"directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:282
msgid "For example, the GitHub API v3 accepts JSON-Encoded POST/PATCH data::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:284
msgid ""
">>> import json\n"
"\n"
">>> url = 'https://api.github.com/some/endpoint'\n"
">>> payload = {'some': 'data'}\n"
"\n"
">>> r = requests.post(url, data=json.dumps(payload))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:291
msgid ""
"Please note that the above code will NOT add the ``Content-Type`` header (so "
"in particular it will NOT set it to ``application/json``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:294
msgid ""
"If you need that header set and you don't want to encode the ``dict`` "
"yourself, you can also pass it directly using the ``json`` parameter (added "
"in version 2.4.2) and it will be encoded automatically:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:303
msgid ""
"Note, the ``json`` parameter is ignored if either ``data`` or ``files`` is "
"passed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:306
msgid "POST a Multipart-Encoded File"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:308
msgid "Requests makes it simple to upload Multipart-encoded files::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:310
msgid ""
">>> url = 'https://httpbin.org/post'\n"
">>> files = {'file': open('report.xls', 'rb')}\n"
"\n"
">>> r = requests.post(url, files=files)\n"
">>> r.text\n"
"{\n"
"  ...\n"
"  \"files\": {\n"
"    \"file\": \"<censored...binary...data>\"\n"
"  },\n"
"  ...\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:323
msgid "You can set the filename, content_type and headers explicitly::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:325
msgid ""
">>> url = 'https://httpbin.org/post'\n"
">>> files = {'file': ('report.xls', open('report.xls', 'rb'), 'application/"
"vnd.ms-excel', {'Expires': '0'})}\n"
"\n"
">>> r = requests.post(url, files=files)\n"
">>> r.text\n"
"{\n"
"  ...\n"
"  \"files\": {\n"
"    \"file\": \"<censored...binary...data>\"\n"
"  },\n"
"  ...\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:338
msgid "If you want, you can send strings to be received as files::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:340
msgid ""
">>> url = 'https://httpbin.org/post'\n"
">>> files = {'file': ('report.csv', 'some,data,to,send\\nanother,row,to,"
"send\\n')}\n"
"\n"
">>> r = requests.post(url, files=files)\n"
">>> r.text\n"
"{\n"
"  ...\n"
"  \"files\": {\n"
"    \"file\": \"some,data,to,send\\\\nanother,row,to,send\\\\n\"\n"
"  },\n"
"  ...\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:353
msgid ""
"In the event you are posting a very large file as a ``multipart/form-data`` "
"request, you may want to stream the request. By default, ``requests`` does "
"not support this, but there is a separate package which does - ``requests-"
"toolbelt``. You should read `the toolbelt's documentation <https://toolbelt."
"readthedocs.io>`_ for more details about how to use it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:359
msgid ""
"For sending multiple files in one request refer to the :ref:`advanced "
"<advanced>` section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:362
msgid ""
"It is strongly recommended that you open files in :ref:`binary mode <tut-"
"files>`. This is because Requests may attempt to provide the ``Content-"
"Length`` header for you, and if it does this value will be set to the number "
"of *bytes* in the file. Errors may occur if you open the file in *text mode*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:370
msgid "Response Status Codes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:372
msgid "We can check the response status code::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:374
msgid ""
">>> r = requests.get('https://httpbin.org/get')\n"
">>> r.status_code\n"
"200"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:378
msgid ""
"Requests also comes with a built-in status code lookup object for easy "
"reference::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:381
msgid ""
">>> r.status_code == requests.codes.ok\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:384
msgid ""
"If we made a bad request (a 4XX client error or 5XX server error response), "
"we can raise it with :meth:`Response.raise_for_status() <requests.Response."
"raise_for_status>`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:388
msgid ""
">>> bad_r = requests.get('https://httpbin.org/status/404')\n"
">>> bad_r.status_code\n"
"404\n"
"\n"
">>> bad_r.raise_for_status()\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  File \"requests/models.py\", line 832, in raise_for_status\n"
"    raise http_error\n"
"requests.exceptions.HTTPError: 404 Client Error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:398
msgid ""
"But, since our ``status_code`` for ``r`` was ``200``, when we call "
"``raise_for_status()`` we get::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:401
msgid ""
">>> r.raise_for_status()\n"
"None"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:404
msgid "All is well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:408
msgid "Response Headers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:410
msgid "We can view the server's response headers using a Python dictionary::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:412
msgid ""
">>> r.headers\n"
"{\n"
"    'content-encoding': 'gzip',\n"
"    'transfer-encoding': 'chunked',\n"
"    'connection': 'close',\n"
"    'server': 'nginx/1.0.4',\n"
"    'x-runtime': '148ms',\n"
"    'etag': '\"e1ca502697e5c9317743dc078f67693f\"',\n"
"    'content-type': 'application/json'\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:423
msgid ""
"The dictionary is special, though: it's made just for HTTP headers. "
"According to `RFC 7230 <https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7230#section-3.2>`_, "
"HTTP Header names are case-insensitive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:427
msgid "So, we can access the headers using any capitalization we want::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:429
msgid ""
">>> r.headers['Content-Type']\n"
"'application/json'\n"
"\n"
">>> r.headers.get('content-type')\n"
"'application/json'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:435
msgid ""
"It is also special in that the server could have sent the same header "
"multiple times with different values, but requests combines them so they can "
"be represented in the dictionary within a single mapping, as per `RFC 7230 "
"<https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7230#section-3.2>`_:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:440
msgid ""
"A recipient MAY combine multiple header fields with the same field name into "
"one \"field-name: field-value\" pair, without changing the semantics of the "
"message, by appending each subsequent field value to the combined field "
"value in order, separated by a comma."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:446
msgid "Cookies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:448
msgid "If a response contains some Cookies, you can quickly access them::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:450
msgid ""
">>> url = 'http://example.com/some/cookie/setting/url'\n"
">>> r = requests.get(url)\n"
"\n"
">>> r.cookies['example_cookie_name']\n"
"'example_cookie_value'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:456
msgid ""
"To send your own cookies to the server, you can use the ``cookies`` "
"parameter::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:459
msgid ""
">>> url = 'https://httpbin.org/cookies'\n"
">>> cookies = dict(cookies_are='working')\n"
"\n"
">>> r = requests.get(url, cookies=cookies)\n"
">>> r.text\n"
"'{\"cookies\": {\"cookies_are\": \"working\"}}'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:466
msgid ""
"Cookies are returned in a :class:`~requests.cookies.RequestsCookieJar`, "
"which acts like a ``dict`` but also offers a more complete interface, "
"suitable for use over multiple domains or paths.  Cookie jars can also be "
"passed in to requests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:471
msgid ""
">>> jar = requests.cookies.RequestsCookieJar()\n"
">>> jar.set('tasty_cookie', 'yum', domain='httpbin.org', path='/cookies')\n"
">>> jar.set('gross_cookie', 'blech', domain='httpbin.org', path='/"
"elsewhere')\n"
">>> url = 'https://httpbin.org/cookies'\n"
">>> r = requests.get(url, cookies=jar)\n"
">>> r.text\n"
"'{\"cookies\": {\"tasty_cookie\": \"yum\"}}'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:481
msgid "Redirection and History"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:483
msgid ""
"By default Requests will perform location redirection for all verbs except "
"HEAD."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:486
msgid ""
"We can use the ``history`` property of the Response object to track "
"redirection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:488
msgid ""
"The :attr:`Response.history <requests.Response.history>` list contains the :"
"class:`Response <requests.Response>` objects that were created in order to "
"complete the request. The list is sorted from the oldest to the most recent "
"response."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:493
msgid "For example, GitHub redirects all HTTP requests to HTTPS::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:495
msgid ""
">>> r = requests.get('http://github.com/')\n"
"\n"
">>> r.url\n"
"'https://github.com/'\n"
"\n"
">>> r.status_code\n"
"200\n"
"\n"
">>> r.history\n"
"[<Response [301]>]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:507
msgid ""
"If you're using GET, OPTIONS, POST, PUT, PATCH or DELETE, you can disable "
"redirection handling with the ``allow_redirects`` parameter::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:510
msgid ""
">>> r = requests.get('http://github.com/', allow_redirects=False)\n"
"\n"
">>> r.status_code\n"
"301\n"
"\n"
">>> r.history\n"
"[]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:518
msgid "If you're using HEAD, you can enable redirection as well::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:520
msgid ""
">>> r = requests.head('http://github.com/', allow_redirects=True)\n"
"\n"
">>> r.url\n"
"'https://github.com/'\n"
"\n"
">>> r.history\n"
"[<Response [301]>]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:530
msgid "Timeouts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:532
msgid ""
"You can tell Requests to stop waiting for a response after a given number of "
"seconds with the ``timeout`` parameter. Nearly all production code should "
"use this parameter in nearly all requests. Failure to do so can cause your "
"program to hang indefinitely::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:537
msgid ""
">>> requests.get('https://github.com/', timeout=0.001)\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n"
"requests.exceptions.Timeout: HTTPConnectionPool(host='github.com', port=80): "
"Request timed out. (timeout=0.001)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:543
msgid "Note"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:545
msgid ""
"``timeout`` is not a time limit on the entire response download; rather, an "
"exception is raised if the server has not issued a response for ``timeout`` "
"seconds (more precisely, if no bytes have been received on the underlying "
"socket for ``timeout`` seconds). If no timeout is specified explicitly, "
"requests do not time out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:553
msgid "Errors and Exceptions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:555
msgid ""
"In the event of a network problem (e.g. DNS failure, refused connection, "
"etc), Requests will raise a :exc:`~requests.exceptions.ConnectionError` "
"exception."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:558
msgid ""
":meth:`Response.raise_for_status() <requests.Response.raise_for_status>` "
"will raise an :exc:`~requests.exceptions.HTTPError` if the HTTP request "
"returned an unsuccessful status code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:562
msgid ""
"If a request times out, a :exc:`~requests.exceptions.Timeout` exception is "
"raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:565
msgid ""
"If a request exceeds the configured number of maximum redirections, a :exc:"
"`~requests.exceptions.TooManyRedirects` exception is raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:568
msgid ""
"All exceptions that Requests explicitly raises inherit from :exc:`requests."
"exceptions.RequestException`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/quickstart.rst:573
msgid "Ready for more? Check out the :ref:`advanced <advanced>` section."
msgstr ""
